The Jets will not risk one player’s potential lack-of development keeping them from the playoffs.

>The two most obvious names to keep an eye on are Derek Carr (Raiders) and Jimmy Garoppolo (49ers). Garoppolo’s injury this year (and lack-of durability throughout his career) makes signing him a bit more tricky, but that could also drive the price down and make him cheaper than Carr.

>I also wouldn’t rule out Daniel Jones, if the Giants were to let him go. He wouldn’t break the bank, would be a great fit in this offense, and his mobility would give coordinator Mike LaFleur another level. What Jones is doing this season with virtually no supporting cast has opened more than a few eyes around the league.

>The crown jewel, obviously, is Lamar Jackson (Ravens). I’d fully expect the Jets to make a serious push to sign him if — and this is a big if — he’s made available. Ride 5 days a week, 2 interval sessions per week, 1 longer session, 2 easy sessions

XC ski 2 days a week

If you ask why they changed it, it's because of this >>127597819, which if you look up, seems to be somewhat of a tradition in some competitions (probably inherited from recreative aristocratic sports tradition or something).

If you ask why they picked and sticked to the new design, then the answer is "branding". The Jules Rimet trophy was given to the winner of the tournament, which sometimes was called the World Cup or World Championship. After the new design was introduced, the "World Cup" unified the name of the trophy, the tournament & the event under the same term and permanently associated those words to FIFA and football itself. It became their disney mickey mouse logo.

>>127607745
Yes but no. In many respects football is way easier to play now than then. Now when you receive a pass, you know the ball will come to you at a good speed and in a smooth trajectory. Back then it bounced all over the place, there was no pitch good enough to allow for teams to play the way they do now. Offside law was way, WAY harsher than it is now, with ANY player being in an offside position being grounds to cancel the play even if they were on the other side of the pitch (and being in the same line was offside). That made certain marking systems look "naive" today, but the fact is defenders were allowed to be much more aggressive and full-game man-marking was far more common.

Skilled attackers had to make use of their pure creativity from the very point they received a pass (which was likely coming at them at chest height or worse, bouncing into their knee right before reaching them) in order to not lose the ball, contain the defender hacking at them, and be able to turn that ball into something productive.

Nowadays that set of skills is less and less necessary since the game looks like billiards and defenses would rather play "blocks" than set up aggressive duels all over the pitch. And one of the reasons higher standards are demanded in technical actions like ball control is precisely that it's gotten SO MUCH easier to play like that (both physically and tactically), that defenses have adapted and therefore demand higher perfection. Think Football vs Basketball. Basketball asks for 0.1% tier precision in technique, Football is a constant struggle against the loss of control. Well, modern Football vs old Football is exactly like that.
